JUST A WORD
To the touring motorist, whether he
free vacationist out to enjoy the clean fresh air, the sunshine and the thrill of mild adventure, or the busy man on business bent, highways are happy ways. To him, the intricate network of motor trails that criss-cross the Middle West are avenues of enjoyment. They lead him from place to place, every mile of which is full of interest.
To enable him to find his way through this maze of traffic ways easily and quickly, the series of maps—of which this is one—have been published by the Standard Oil Company (Indiana). Every care has been taken to make these maps accurate, and it is hoped that the motorist who gets them will find them helpful.
Throughout the territory the Standard Oil Company (Indiana) has organized a complete distribution of its motor necessities, Red Crown Gasoline, Red Crown Ethyl Gasoline, Solite Gasoline, Polarine Motor Oils and greases, ISO-VIS Motor Oil and ISO-VIS Lubricant. There are upward of six thousand company-owned and operated Service Stations and many thousand more privately owned filling stations and garages where the products of the Standard Oil Company (Indiana) may be secured.
Wherever the motorist sees the Red Crown or other sign of this company displayed, he may
lari lie

be certain he will obtain the genuine product advertised. These products always are uniform in quality and dependable.
In the Service Stations you will find clean, sanitary, well - ventilated comfort stations and lavatory facilities; plenty of water for your radiator and free air for your tires. And wherever you go you will find that the enviable reputation
OIOD
0103
ETHYL GASOLINE CORPORATION ,
for efficiency and courtesy which our station attendants have won, is merited.
If, at anytime, you are in doubt as to whicb-of several routes you should take, drop into any Standard Oil Company (Indiana) Service Station and ask the attendant. He usually is well informed as to road conditions in the neighborhood of his station and he always is glad to help make your touring a pleasant experience.
The Service Station attendant is ambitious and is working for advancement in this organization. He wants to serve you cheerfully and well. Please do not embarrass him by offering a tip. He does not want-it, for he understands, and he wants you to understand, that whatever he can do to make your journey a pleasant one he will do gladly. His effort to please you is but one expression of the multitude of things to make up Standard Oil Company (Indiana) service.

The Birch Hill golf course is west of Dearborn, and to the north, on Warren avenue, is the Hawthorne Valley Club with a 36 hole course. Increases such as shown in the above figures have occurred in every desirable phase of the city’s development. Plans of the city government and the public service corporations are based on the needs of a far greater population than Detroit now has. And in anticipating this demand of the future more than strong faith and enthusiastic vision were depended upon for estimates. Millions of dollars are involved in this extention work and sound practical methods were used for arriving at approximate figures.
With every increase in the size and activities of the city, real estate has gone up in value. From 1 to 75 million dollars have been mad$ by automobile manufacturers and in one case a fortune of $750,000,000 has come to one man in the industry. But the combined earnings of all of these is far less than the amount that has been made in Detroit real estate.
One case of real estate profits which is in no way unusual, is that of a lot on West Grand Boulevard. In 1904, when the Stormfeltz-Loveley Company was started there were but two houses between Grand River and Second, on the Boulevard. By 1914 this company had subdivided a large tract there and lots which originally sold for about $2,800 were valued at $8,000. sold for $120,000.

transcription:
PRICE COUNTY
The lands of the Price County tract lie gener illy high and rolling, above the range of early and late frosts, lengthening the growing season considerably.
They are naturally drained by good sized s\ earns of clear spring water winding through the valleys with natural meadcws of blue joint on either side. The hardwood ridges running parallel with the streams present long and gentle slopes, occasionally breaking into abrupt bluffs.
The landscape is pleasing to the eye and when the lands are cleared up and improved, will present a view not very different from the farms of Green County, Wisconsin, the famous cheese country.
CLIMATE
The climate of this locality is characterized by a large amount of sunshine. Winter sets in about December 1 st, and is a clear and steady cold. The air is dry and bracing. The Summers are warm in day and cool of nights. The average rain and snowfall is 36 inches, distributed principally in warm showers through the Summer months, or the growing season.
The large water surface of Lake Superior on the North and of Lake Michigan on the East and the warm air currents from the South through the Mississippi River Valley on the West combine in giving this region a more even temperature and a larger rainfall than are obtained by the States west of Lake Superior.
GRASSES AND CLOVERS
Grasses and clovers may be classed among the natural resources of the country; for they are found everywhere growing wild, along the roads and among brush wherever the sunlight can get in. Red and white clover, blue grass and timothy as common and rank as weeds in other countries, impress the newcomer on every hand with their value for stock raising and the dairy business.
The settler need not wait to clear his land of stumps. Cattle and sheep confined on uncleared land will soon destroy most of the brush, which seeded to clovers and grasses without plowing will furnish the best pasture the second year and good yields of hay the third year. A few acres of the easiest clearing planted to corn will fill the silo with the best of winter feed.
The rich pasturage of Upper Wisconsin is the foundation of untold wealth, as it insures stability and regularity of income for its farmers every year.
A stony field seeded down to timothy and clover will ordinarily produce as much in dollars and cents per acre for a series of years as it could be made to produce in other crops if all cleared up for cultivation.
The Clovers
Used for pasture and hay, the clovers have thus become identified with the grasses, though they belong to an entirely different family of plants, and have other uses of value not shared in by the grasses. Where the clovers
flourish, other crops will grow and the soils will not run out. All leguminous plants, aside from their rich food value for animal life, are peculiarly feeders of plant life. So it means much to find in a country not only a variety of naturally rich soils, but to find also, growing there naturally, a variety of leguminous plants of themselves of great food value and possessed of the quality to preserve and restore the fertility of the soil. Every practical farmer and stockman will appreciate the importance of the claims made for the Upper Wisconsin’s heavy yields of clover. Such heavy and continuous crops of all legumes are the result of the copious rainfall and fertile soil with which Northern Wisconsin is especially favored.
STOCK RAISING
CATTLE—In addition to the dairy cow, beef cattle thrive on the rich pastures of this region. A two year old steer, feeding on the wild pastures, will put on sufficient weight in a single season to be turned off as tender and marketable beef of the very best quality.
SHEEP—Mutton raising is profitable and easy industry where feed is so abundant and the animals are so free from every disease. The more rolling lands, are very much cheaper than others and furnish the best range for large flocks of sheep. We have thousands of acres of these lands, which cannot be excelled for this purpose. While rough and sometimes stony they have rich clay soil, producing large yields of clover and grasses generally well supplied with pure running water. There is enough tillable land with these lands to raise winter feed. Large sheep raisers are especially invited to inspect this proposition.
SWINE—Young pigs thrive on milk and clover pasture and corn, barley and peas will do the rest to turn them into valuable pork. Barley and clover-fed hogs produce fine bacon and hams with a reputation all their own. Pork raised in this region is sweet and free from disease.
POULTRY—The raising of poultry has now become one of the important departments on the farm. With a good local demand, and the large city markets only a few hours distant a quick cash market is always ready to receive your surplus of poultry and eggs at good prices.
Homeseekers Prosper in Wisconsin
Today the homeseeker is looking back to the old homestead farm of the East and of the South, which was hewn out of the heavy hardwood timber and he remembers the rank growth of blue grass timothy, orchard grass and the clovers, where fat stock, dairy products and grain were always grown and are still grown every year with certainty. He cannot conclude otherwise than that every stump and every tree somehow stands as a guarantee of the stability of the crop production of these farms. The value of such lands has reached $200.00 and up per acre and, when farmed with stock, they never wear out. State and U. S. Government Reports on Agriculture, show THAT THE ONCE TIMBERED LANDS LEAD ALL OTHERS IN STEADY AND EVERY YEAR PRODUCTION. This fact has been proven and it is this that is bringing homeseekers to Wisconsin, where a crop failure is practically unknown.
We will sell any of our lands for cash or upon easy terms if desired. A small down payment gives you immediate possession, under our form of land contract, and our plan of extended payments makes it possible for the poor man to provide himself and family with a good farm home of their own. We Guarantee you a good title with the deed to the property.	AMERICAN IMMIGRATION COMPANY,
Hayward, Wisconsin

SO
EXPLANATION OF INDEX.
Key numbers are in parentheses, thus (D6).
County seats in capitals, thus ASHLAND.
Money Order Post off ices are shown thus *.
Railroads and express offices shown by Italic figures, thus 9, 11.
Telegraph offices are shown thus ©.
The letter and numeral In parentheses directly following the name of the town correspond to the letters and numerals on the margin of the map. To locate a given town trace a line between the given letter on opposite sides of the map and one between the given numeral on opposite sides of the map and at or very near the junction of these lines will be found the town desired.
Italic figures folowing the key numbers indicate the railroad or railroads upon which the town is situated and also the express company going into the town.

ALSO AGENT FOR THE SALE OF THE FOLLOWING
For working WOOD, the best ever offered to the public—for which diplomas and medals, from various Associations have been received. Built by Ball & Ballard, Fay & Co., &c.
DANIEL’S IMPROVED PLANING MACHINES.
Having bad long experience in building these VALUABLE MACHINES, and having recently made great improvements in the style and manner of operating them, we feel confident we can supply the public with Machines of superior quality. The advantages of our new FEED WORK are :
1st—Of planing when the carriage is moving either way, and having any desirable velocity.
2d—The carriage is drawn from its centre by a rack underneath, and is secure from shavings.
3d—it is drawn by a pinion abovo the rack, thus preventing the carriage from rising when in motion.
4th—All belts and gears below are dispensed with, and those above are out of the way of shavings, &c., and the pinions are in gear at all times.
5th—-The shipper handles are all safely and conveniently arranged.
---------------4	---------------*
For Planing Straight and out of Wind. Patented, Aug. 22,1854.
THIS PLANER works with Cylindrical Revolving Cutters, like the cutters of the celebrated Woodworth Machines, and does not interfere with the Woodworth Patent. 87 45'0 —145 55 DESCRIPTION OF THE TOPOGRAPHIC MAP OE THE UNITED STATES
The United States Geological Survey is making a topographic map of the United States. This work has been in progress since 1882, and about one-fifth of the area of the country, including Alaska, has been mapped. The mapped areas are widely scattered, nearly every State being represented, as shown on the progress map accompanying each annual report of the Director.
This great map is being published in atlas sheets of convenient size, which are bounded by parallels and meridians. The four-cornered division of land corresponding to an atlas sheet is called a quadrangle. The sheets are of approximately the same size: the paper dimensions are 20 by 16^- inches; the map occupies about 17^-inches of height and 11|- to 16 inches of width, the latter varying with latitude. Three scales, however, are employed. The largest scale is 1:62500, or very nearly one mile to one inch; i. e., one linear mile on the ground is represented by one linear inch on the map. This scale is used for the thickly settled or industrially important parts of the country. For the greater part of the country an intermediate scale of 1:125000, or about two miles to one inch, is employed. ' A third and still smaller scale of 1:250000, or about four miles to one inch, has been used in the desert regions of the far West. A few special maps on larger scales are made of limited areas in mining districts. The sheets on the largest scale cover 15' of latitude by 15' of longitude; those on the intermediate scale, 30' of latitude by 30' of longitude ; and those on the smallest scale, 1° of latitude by 1° of longitude.
The features shown on this map may, for convenience, be classed in three groups: (1) xoater, including seas, lakes, ponds, rivers and other streams, canals, swamps, etc.; (2) relief, including mountains, hills, valleys, cliffs, etc.; (3) culture, i. e., works of man, such as towns, cities, roads, railroads, boundaries, etc. The conventional signs used for these features are grouped below. Variations appear in some maps of earlier dates.
All water features are shown in blue, the smaller streams and canals in full blue lines, and
J	I
the larger streams, lakes, and the sea by blue water lining. Certain streams, however, which flow during only a part of the year, their beds being dry at other times, are shown, not by full lines, but by lines of dots and dashes. Ponds which are dry during a part of the year are shown by oblique parallel lines. Salt-water marshes are shown by horizontal ruling interspersed with tufts of blue, and fresh-water marshes and swamps by bhie tufts with broken horizontal lines.
Relief is shown by contour lines in brown. Each contour passes through points which have the same altitude. One who follows a con-| tour on the ground will go neither uphill nor downhill, but on a level. By the use of contours not only are the shapes of the plains, hills, and mountains shown, but also the elevations. The line of the seacoast itself is a contour line, the datum or zero of elevation being mean sea level. The contour line at, say, 20 feet above sea level is the line that would be the seacoast if the sea were to rise or the land to sink 20 feet. Such a line runs back up the valleys and forward around the points of hills and spurs. On a gentle slope this contour line is far from the present coast line, while on a steep slope it is near it. Thus a succession of these contour lines far apart on the map indicates a gentle slope; if close together, a steep slope; and if they run together in one line, as if each contour were vertically under the one above it, they indicate a cliff. In many parts of the country are depressions or hollows with no outlets. The contours of course surround these, j just as they surround hills. Those small hollows known as sinks are usually indicated by hachures. or short dashes, on the inside of the curve. The contour interval, or the vertical distance in feet I between one contour and the next, is stated at the bottom of each map. This interval varies
*	i
according to the character of the area mapped; in a flat country it may be as small as 10 feet, in a mountainous region it may be 200 feet. Certain contours, usually every fifth one, are accompanied by numbers stating elevation above sea level, j Many other heights, instrumentally determined, j
are also given, the number in each case being placed in close proximity to the point to which it applies.
The works of man are shown in black, in Avhich color all lettering also is printed. Boundaries, such as State, county, city, land-grant, reservation, etc., are shown by broken lines of different kinds and weights. Cities are indicated by black blocks, representing the built-up portions, and country houses by small black squares. Roads are shown by fine double lines (full- for the better roads, dotted for the inferior ones), trails by single dotted lines, and railroads by full black lines with cross lines. Other cultural features are represented by conventions which are easily understood.
The sheets composing the topographic atlas are designated by the name of a principal town or of some prominent natural feature within the district, and the names of adjoining published sheets are printed on the margins. The sheets are sold at five cents each when fewer than 100 copies are purchased, but when they are ordered in lots of 100 or more copies, whether of the same sheet or of different sheets, the price is two cents each.
The topographic map is the base on which the facts of geology and the mineral resources of a quadrangle are represented. The topographic and geologic maps of a quadrangle are finally bound together, accompanied by a description of the district, to form a folio of the Geologic Atlas of the United States. The folios are sold at twenty-five cents each, except such as are unusually comprehensive, which are priced accordingly.
Applications for the separate topographic maps or for folios of the Geologic Atlas should be accompanied by the cash or by post-office money order (not postage stamps), and should be addressed to—
THE DIRECTOR,
United States Geological Survey,
Washington, D. C.
September, 1899.

Northern Wisconsin The Ideal Vacation Land
Just a few hours easy travel from Chicago and Milwaukee or St. Paul-Minneapolis, there is one of the greatest vacation lands of America—indeed, of all the world.
It is the Country of Big Woods and Many Waters—in Northern Wisconsin.
Its scenic charm, its many opportunities for different forms of recreation, its quiet, its coolness, the genuine hospitality of its people, and above all its easy accessibility, make this sylvan region the resort, the refuge, and the playground for hundreds of thousands every year.
518,000 Acres of Lakes
Northern Wisconsin has room for them all, fishermen, campers, cottagers, hotel guests. You could lose the entire area of a New England state or two in its cool pine forests. There are no less than 518,000 acres of lakes—so many individual patches of silvery, crystal waters that it probably would take an astronomer to count them all. Besides, there are rivers and streams innumerable.

No true fisherman need come back empty handed from the fishing trip in these waters. This is the real habitat of those fighting game fish, the tiger muskellunge, the bass, and the trout. There is an abundance of pickerel, perch, and pike, too—in fact, every variety of toothsome fresh water fish.
For the Fisherman
Which one of these fishing grounds to give your personal attention, is something of a problem. There are many of them—and there are different kinds of fishing, and a myriad styles of doing it. If we knew your personal preference, we would try to say right offhand. Perhaps the best that is possible in a general way is to mention some of the places that fishermen have tried to keep secret, but whose popularity has betrayed them; such good old-sure-to-catch-fish standbys as Boulder Junction, Hazelhurst, Minocqua, Sayner, Star Lake, Tomahawk, Trout Lake, and Arbor Vitae.
At most of these fishing grounds, the angler who lacks an outfit can provide himself with tackle and bait for every sort of fishing, together with canoes, boats, and camping outfits. Here, too, the services of experienced
guides are procurable at moderate rates for those who feel that fishing means a secluded place, ‘‘off all by myself.”
As you know, the state of Wisconsin is deeply appreciative of the welfare of its citizens and guests in this matter of recreation. It makes many provisions for maintaining and enhancing the charms of this wonderful outdoors country. Among these attentions, the fishermen certainly fare very well. The Wisconsin Conservation Commission through a highly developed system of hatcheries, keeps the fishing grounds constantly stocked with abundant supplies of all the native food fishes.
For the Entire Family
But Northern Wisconsin is not for the happy fisherman alone. There is much of interest, of health, of wholesome pleasure and of real rest up there for every man, woman and child. It is a great place for the entire family. If you like to swim, these cool, clear waters are the bracing tonic for a “bear” of an appetite. If you are fond of canoeing, here are the famous water trails known to the early explorers and the Indians before them, and today in pretty much the same primeval solitude as when the
m

m
voyageurs first dipped a paddle in them. Hiking? Here’s the hiker’s seventh heaven of delight—-in the cool, deep forests, with their underground of velvety needles and cones.
You don’t even have to leave your game of golf behind when you go to Northern Wisconsin. At many different points you will find a welcome to a sporty course. There is one, of something over 200 acres, overlooking famous Lake Minocqua and all the beautiful reach of country to the Southeast of Minocqua. Visitors are allowed, upon payment of a small fee, all the membership privileges of the Minocqua Heights Golf and Country Club.
But maybe you don’t want to engage in any such active sports as golf, tennis, swimming, trout-stream whipping or muskie-fighting. Maybe you just want to loaf and invite your soul. You can do it to the queen’s taste.
Anything that Suits Your Purse and Fancy

Watchful Waiting
which most appeals to you. Or you can settle down to the convenience and social life of a well-managed hotel. Anything that suits your purse and fancy, Northern Wisconsin has for you.
How to Reach Northern Wisconsin
From early in June to mid-September, special efforts are made to cater to the travel needs and pleasures of all vacationers. Fine fast trains of the Chicago, Milwaukee and St. Paul Ry. run daily from Chicago, Milwaukee, St. Paul, Minneapolis and other centers, direct to the land of woods and waters. They carry sleeping cars, coaches, dining cars serving all meals.
Schedules are most conveniently arranged. The fisherman going up for but a single day of his favorite sport has an opportunity to be on his favorite lake, all breakfasted and ready for the first cast, early in the morning after he has left town. The business-man can lock his desk of a Friday evening, spend a restful week-end with his family at some Northern Wisconsin lake, and be back on the job on Monday morning.
Where Hotels are Superfluous
A Big Time for Little Money
Again, the fact of inexpensiveness adds to Northern Wisconsin’s attractions. Reduced round-trip fares are in effect, May to September, and these, too, are classified to meet all needs. Certain of them apply for the weekends, and for special holidays like May 30th and July 4th; others cover thirty-day periods, amply covering the normal vacation time—and still others are limited only by the season, which ends October 31 st.
If Northern Wisconsin is in your mind now, you have only to call on your nearest railroad ticket agent, or any representative of the “Milwaukee” Railroad listed on page 13 of this folder for full information about where to go, how to get there, and what it will cost you. He will give you a lot of help—even, in Chicago, having your fishing licenses ready for you, thanks to the courtesy of the Wisconsin Conservation Commission. Descriptive map folders, booklets and other literature covering your inquiries exactly are always available.
If you have ever been to Northern Wisconsin, you know all we have said is true—and much more. If you haven’t been there, go this year. You will never need to be urged to go again.

WISCONSIN
POINTS OF INTEREST
Historic and scenic points of interest, with brief description of outstanding features, together with most convenient approaches by automobile.
(S) indicates locations of Standard 71 Oil Company (Ind.) Service Stations JJ
ABLEMAN. The Narrows, an ancient canyon. 9 miles W. of Baraboo on W. 33, W. 154.
ALGOMA, Kewaunee Co., a Lake Michigan town having (s)also Krohns and Alaska lakes nearby. It is said to be one of the coolest spots in the state during the summer. W. 1 7, W. 54.
AMBERG. Beecher Lake, between Amberg and Pembine on W. 57 is where Henry Ward Beecher first began to preach to the lumberjacks.
APPLETON, Outagamie Co. A water-power and paper (s)mill city on Fox R., near Lake Winnebago. Lawrence College, one of the state’s oldest educational institutions. Indian mounds. U. S. 10, U. S. 41, W. 47, W. 125.
APOSTLE ISLANDS. Famous resort for sufferers of hay fever. Gateway to Chequamegon Bay. The eight lighthouses have no rivals on the Great Lakes. The Twenty Apostles, separated by broad channels from 75 to 200 feet deep, could shelter the combined navies of the entire world. Near Ashland on U. S. 2, W. 131. BAILEYS HARBOR, on the E. shore of Peninsula of Door Co. Nearby is Kangaroo Lake. To the N. are Moonlight Bay, North Bay, Cana Island light house, Eagles Nest, Sunset Park, Lovers Lane, Birch Grove, Burned Hallow, and Indian Burial Grounds. W. 78. BARABOO. Man Mound, Man Mound park, 2 miles N. (s)of Baraboo. Devils Lake Park, 2 miles S. of Baraboo 9 miles W. is Ableman, where The Narrows, an ancient canyon, is located. U. S. 12, W. 13, W. 33. BELMONT. Wisconsin's first Capitol, a frame building which is still standing, preserved, in a small state park near Belmont. U. S. 118, W. 126.
BELOIT. Turtle Effigy and other mounds on the Beloit (s)College grounds. U. S. 51, W. 14, W. 92, W. 13, W. 26.
BERLIN, Green Lake Co. is close to some of the most (s) beautiful Wisconsin Lakes, especially Green Lake, Puckaway Lake, Silver Lake, and the Fox R. W. 49, W. 116.
BLACK RIVER FALLS. Highest waterfall in Wisconsin, (s) 160 feet high. U. S. 12, W. 27, W. 54.
BRULE. Brule Park Lands are located up and down the Brule Valley, along the Brule R. Trout fishing. U. S. 2. Buttes des Morts, Winnebago Co., N. W. of Oshkosh. The name meaning “Hills of the Dead" was given to historic Indian battle ground and canoe portage between Green Bay and Portage. A popular fishing ground, especially early in the season when white bass “run" in the Wolf R. U. S. 110, W. 1 16. CAMP DOUGLAS. In a driftless area containing many strange earth formations, bluffs, buttes and crags of limestone that tower like castles on the Rhine. Also State Army Artillery range. W. 94, N. of U. S. 12, U. S. 16.
CEDARBURG, Ozaukee Co. Interesting old German settlement on Milwaukee R. This river has cut into limestone masses at places, creating beautiful scenic spots, used by many art-sketching classes and as background or “location" for motion picture productions. W. 57, W. 143.
CHETEK. Lake Chetek is a popular summer resort. In-(s)dian battlegrounds and burial mounds. U. S. 53. CHIPPEWA FALLS, Irvine Park. 300 acres of natural (s)beauty. Miles of winding drives; zoo with all native animals, and herds of deer, elk and buffalo; virgin woods, and pretty scenes. An added point of interest is the Wissota dam, 1 Ya miles long. w. 29, U. S. 53. DE SOTO, Vernon Co. Winneshiek Park, containing burial grounds of the great Indian Chief Winneshiek. Interesting view of Mississippi R. S. from La Crosse on W. 82, W. 35.
DEVILS LAKE, Sauk Co., just south of Baraboo is a small but beautiful lake, placed among high masses of granite which tower in places 600 feet high. 1,400 acres of surrounding area have been made a state park. W. 123.
EAGLE RIVER. Embraced by a chain of 27 connected lakes, headwaters of the Wisconsin R. W. 26, W. 70, W. 63. Northern Forest Park is located on U. S. 51, N. W. of Eagle R.
EPHRAIM. One of the oldest settlements in Door Co., is located immediately north of Peninsula Park. It was settled by a colony of Scandinavian farmers and fishermen who came to it under the leadership of a Moravian Missionary. Quaint buildings. Good scenery. N. E. of Sturgeon Bay. W. 17. Gills Rock on W. 78, at the end of Sister Bay Peninsula, is a quaint fisherman’s village.
GALESVILLE. Lake Marinuka. Stop at Arctic Springs, at the grave of Princess Marinuka, grand-daughter of Chief Decorah. Historic Gale College founded in 1859. U. S. 53, W-35. FLORENCE. Florence Co., is located at the boundary between Wisconsin and Northern Peninsula of Michigan, in typical north country of rushing streams, beautiful lakes and deep woods; popular with trout fishermen because of Brule, Paint, Menominee and Pine Rivers. U. S. 2, W-101, U. S. 41.
FISH CREEK. Door Co., lies at the base of an immense limestone bluff rising 200 feet from the water’s edge. A magnificent view of the surrounding country may be obtained from this elevation. N. E. of Sturgeon Bay. W-17.
FOUNTAIN CITY. “Indian Head” sentinel on the Mississippi. Natural stone face—44 feet from chin to forehead. W-35, W-95.
GAYS MILLS. Splendid view of the Kickapoo R. curving its sleepy way through the narrow valley. 900 acres of cherry and apple orchards which, in blossom time, are a scene of exquisite beauty. W-131.
GREEN BAY. Oldest city in Wisconsin. U. S. 41, U. S. 141; <8)W-29, W-32, W-54, W-78. Red Banks on the shores of Green Bay and 15 miles N. of that city, was the scene of early Indian exploitations. Marks of Indian ownership still remain.
HATFIELD. Beautiful Lake Arbutus, surrounded by Pine Forest;
a delightful resort. On county trunk K, just off W-54. HOLMEN. Trempealeau Mountain, where Perrott, the French explorer, landed in 1685. It is part of Perrott Park, a tract of land consisting of 1,000 acres. U. S. 53.
KESHENA FALLS. An old Indian Camp. The falls are surrounded by deep foliage which is almost primeval in its nature. W-55, W-47.
KILBOURN. Sauk City, Wisconsin R. Dells. Remarkable scenery and geological formations—in most part the result of a remarkable geological phenomenon in which the Wisconsin, ages ago, changed its course and carved a passage through the limestone masses that now form the Dells. Kilbourn: W-23, W-13, W-135, U. S. 12, U. S. 16. Sauk City: U. S. 12, W-I36, W-13, W-81, W-60.
LAC DU FLAMBEAU, in Vilas Co., N. W. of Minocqua, and 5 miles N. of W-70 with which it is connected by a well-maintained highway. It is an old Indian village with an Indian burial ground. Now reservation headquarters. It has a large Indian population which is interesting to tourists.
LA CROSSE. Grandad Bluff, at the head of Main Street, is the (sihighest point in La Crosse Co. Splendid view of the Mississippi Valley. U. S. 53, U. S. 16, W-35, U. S. 61, W-33. U. S. 61 from La Crosse N. to Winona, is one of the most picturesque drives along the maiestic Mississippi. W-35 from La Crosse So. to Lynxville follows the river all the way; very good scenery.
LAKE GENEVA. Walworth Co. Old but attractive and profs) gressive village at E. end of lake of same name; summer resort. U. S. 12, W-36, W-50.
LAKE MILLS. Jefferson Co. Nearby are Rock Lake and Aztalan (8)Park. The park is the site of prehistoric earthworks. W-30, • W-89.
LAKE WINNEBAGO. Largest inland lake in Wisconsin. Swimming, fishing, yachting; in the winter season, ice boating and skating. (See Oshkosh.)
LAONA. Forest Co., is a modern lumber town in the heart of some of Wisconsin’s finest remaining virgin forests. Off U S 8 W-32
LYNXVILLE. The “Winmsheikbeautiful area of back water of the upper Mississippi Game Preserve. Proposed as a National Park. W-35.
MADISON. State Capitol. Observatory Hill and University of (8) Wisconsin grounds. Bear effigy, West Washington St. near Vilas Park. Eagle Effigy on State Hospital grounds at Men-dota. U. S. 12, U. S. 18, U. S. 151, W-19, W-13, W-69, W-11. MAIDEN ROCK. One of the beauty spots of the Upper Mississippi. W-35.
MANITOWOC. Maribcl Caves, on W-17, N. of Manitowoc, con-(8) sists of a number of limestone caves which are exceedingly interesting to explore. U. S. 141, U. S. 10, W-3 1. MARINETTE. Marinette Co. Surrounded by country cut over but rapidly being re-forested. Famous trout waters and inland lakes. Near Cauldron Falls. U. S. 41, W-64.
MELLEN. Copper Falls Park in a forest and lake country. Five waterfalls and Rock R. gorge. Near Mellen on W-13, W-77. MERRILL. Lincoln Co., has virgin timber scenery; interesting (s)25-mile drive on W-91 along Wisconsin R. to Tomahawk, passing Grandfather Falls (now water power site). U. S. 5 1, W-63, W-64, W-91.
MINOCQUA. Oneida Co., is built on land that originally was an island, although now it is connected with Mainland by filled roads and bridges. U. S. 51, W-70. The Lac du Flambeau Indian Reservation is 1 1 miles N. Minocqua.
NECEDAH. Petenall Rock towers over the banks of the Wisconsin River. W-21, W-80.
NEENAH. It was formerly the log cabin home of the territorial (s)governor, Doty, and it also has many other landmarks of early explorers and missionaries. It is across city from Menasha, a city of similar interests. U. S. 41, W-150, W-12 5, W-l 14.
NEW QLARUS. An odd little town transplanted from the Old World with Swiss people, architecture, language and customs.
1	S. of Madison W-69, W39.
OSHKOSH. Winnebago Co., is on the Western shore of Lake (a)Wimicbago, rich in places of historic interest concerned with activities of old Menominee and Winnebago tribes. U. S. 41, U. S. 110, W-21, W-44 and W-26.
PLYMOUTH. Sheboygan Co. is the world’s greatest center for (s)production and marketing of “American Style” cheese. W-23, W-57, W-67.
PLATTEVILLE. Lead and zinc mines near Platteville. U. S. (s) 1 18, W-14 and W-80.
PORTAGE. Marquette and Joliet, portaged here from the Fox fs)to the Wisconsin R. in 1673 on the way to their famous voyage down the Mississippi. Government canal 2 M. in length connects the Fox and Wisconsin R. here. U. S. 16, U. S. 51, W-33, W-81.
PRAIRIE DU CHIEN. Second oldest city in the state in midst of good scenery and places of historic interest. U. S. 18, U. S. 61. Nelson Dewey State Park near Prairie du Chien, a short distance off U. S. 18. Clam and Pearl fisheries about Prairie du Chien on W-35.
STURGEON BAY. The country N. of Sturgeon Bay is often (s)called “The Cherry Land of Wisconsin.” W-17, W-78. SHAWANO. Spirit Rock in Shawano Co. is 3 miles N. of (s)Shawano. W-22, W-29, W-47. W-55. John Corn’s Cabin about 15 miles N. of Shawano along W-55. The MenOminee Indian Reservation, N. of Shawano, extends about 15 miles along W-55, W-47. Tourist Park on the north shore of Shawano Lake on W-55.
SPARTA. Camp Sparta, one of the best artillery camps in the (s)U. S. Co. Trunk B from Sparta; U. S. 16, W-2 7, W-71.
Castle Rock, about 3 miles N. W. of Sparta.
ST. CROIX FALLS. Interstate Park near St. Croix Falls. Marvelous dells cut into solid rock by rushing waters of the St. Croix R. U. S. 8, W-35, W-87.
THREE LAKES. Oneida Co., just S. of Eagle R., is a small village surrounded by lakes in the heart of the summer resort country. W-26, W-32.
TOMAHAWK. Lincoln Co., is in the center of beautiful lake (sidistrict and virgin forests. U. S. 51, W-86, W-91.
TOMAH. United States Government Indian School. 200 stu-(s)dents enrolled, representing five tribes. U. S. 12, W-21. VIROQUA. Monument Rock 3 miles S. of Viroqua on W-2 7. (s)Viroqua is on U. S. 61, W-11. W-27, W-56 WAUSAU. Marathon Co., is the largest city N. of Central (s)Wisconsin; surrounded by productive farms and deep wilderness areas. State Park. U. S. 51, W-29, W-52. N. of Wausau Co. Trunk N, is Rib Hill, the highest point in the state, 1940 feet above sea level.
WAUPACA. Waupaca Co., is near the famous Waupaca Chain (s)of Lakes called “The Killarneys of the West.” U. S. 10, W-49, W-54. W-22.
WEST SALEM. Northward is Mindoro Cut, second largest in (s)the U. S. A winding scenic drive. U. S. 16, W-l 08. WONEWOC. Spiritualist Grounds in Unity Park. A pretty park overlooking the Baraboo River Valley. W-33. S. E. Union Center.

The railroad stations in the city of Menominee contributed 4,745 carloads of Forest Products, 31 carloads of Farm Products and the entire 9,873 carloads of Other Products. Among the forest products there were 1,073 carloads of paper and paper pulp, 351 carloads of ties and 3,048 carloads of luqiber and posts. The lumber that is shipped from these stations consists partly of’lumber and millwork handled by the Menominee lumber dealers. A good deal of the lumber is from western and southern sources which is reshipped for distribution from Menominee and therefore not strictly a Menominee County product.
The northern part of the county was the source of most of the carload shipments of logs, with 372 cars loaded out by the stations on the New Line and the Metropolitan branches of the Chicago and Northwestern Railway. Pulpwood and bolts were quite generally distributed among the stations in the central and northern part of the county. Hermansville is the principal shipper of forest products, outside of the Menominee city stations, with 1,317 cars of lumber and 455 cars of fuel wood and slabs. Daggett, with 441 carloads, and Ingalls, with 312 carloads, rank next in order as shippers of these products.
The Chicago-Northwestern Railway stations from Menominee northward to Nadeau ship the bulk of the potatoes marketed. Hay came principally from Harris, v Wilson, Powers, Hermansville, Nadeau and Carney, and sugar beets from Stephen-, son, Banat, Wilson and Whitney. Wilson, Stephenson and Daggett were the heaviest shippers of livestock.
Menominee City’s diversified industries account for the bulk of other products except the 2,545 carloads of coal which is shipped to Menominee for distribution.
The Wisconsin and Michigan R. R., which extends from Iron Mountain, Michigan, to Peshtigo Harbor, Wisconsin, crosses the western part of the county in a north and south direction through Faithom, Nathan, Swanson and Longrie. This line and the Chicago, Milwaukee and St. Paul Railway reach the city of Menominee from the Marinette, Wisconsin, side of the river.
This network of railroads gives Menominee County about 145 miles of main line trackage and places practically all parts of the county, except the sparsely settled portions of Gourley, Cedarville and Ingallston Townships, within 6 or 8 miles of a railroad.
The Ann Arbor R. R. car ferry crossing Lake Michigan with docks at Menominee and Frankfort gives direct connections for the northwest and southeast destinations.

The railroads are supplemented by an extensive system of improved roads. US-41 extends northward from Menominee to Powers and eastward to Escanaba. This highway and US-2, which extends westward through Spalding, Hermansville and Iron Mountain, parallel the Chicago-Northwestern Railway. M-69 leaves US-2 and US-41 between Bark River and Narenta in Delta County and extends northwestward through Menominee County parallel to the Metropolitan Branch of the Chicago-Northwestern Railway. M-35, known as the “Bay Shore Road,” parallels the shore of Green Bay from Menominee to Escanaba. From these trunk line highways, a tributary system of improved county and township roads lead to the villages, farming communities and power plants. In addition to these standard highways, a considerable mileage of “woods” and “plains” roads give access to the western and northern portions of the county where settlement is very sparse and nonpermanent. These roads, while receiving but little maintenance work beyond some attention to bridges, are used to a surprising extent even for automobile traffic by woodsmen, fishermen, hunters and tourists during the season from May to November.

Land now in private ownership may be divided into two broad classes, i. e., used land, land that is owned for the purpose of producing a return to its owner; and idle land, land that is owned because of its supposed ability to produce a return to an owner that will use it. The value of either ciass of land is fixed by the profit that the owners do obtain or expect to obtain from the use of the land. Lands from which a high profit is regularly obtained or safely anticipated have a relatively high value, and those on which profit is or seems likely to be either low or uncertain will
■ -V
have little or no value. Development and use of the high value lands is ordinarily prompt and complete while that of the low value lands is usually meagre or lags and hesitates until the assurance of profit through its use becomes apparent.
The certainty of profit from the ownership of any land is effected by many things other than the land and its owner. Among these are the use that is being made or that is likely to be made of the neighboring and other lands, which may react either favorably or unfavorably on the lands of any owner. This relation of land use to the lands of other owners gives the public an interest in the use that all land-owners have or plan for their lands. It also gives the individual land-owner an equally legitimate interest in the public’s plans and policies for the development and use of his own and other private or publicly owned lands.; Such plans and poli- f-"* ^ cies can be expected to be properly effective only when they are in agreement with the public good and the interests of the present and future owners. They should find their basis in the character of the land, its environment, its value, the land-owners and their purpose or “intent” in ownership. This basis the Land Economic Survey attempts to furnish by its inventory which is presented in (1) the soil and farm-forest maps to provide information on the character of the land and its environment, (2) the land ownership maps to designate who owns the land, (3) the figures that were taken from the county treasurer’s records to establish existing value under present uses, and (4) the intent in ownership classification, which was obtained with the assistance of the township supervisors, to define the purpose for which the land is owned.
When, the purpose or “intent in ownership” is- know® /for all tAe land in a county, it becomes a simple matter to locate, classify and group those lands that are owned for the same purpose or intent in ownership. Such a classification and grouping will facilitate the development of idle lands and the application of better uses to used lands, for since the numerous individual owners that make up each intent in ownership will have a common interest or reason in ownership, it naturally follows that they can from then on be treated as a unit or group in considering and devising plans and policies for encouraging development, increasing production, improving land use or extending any public action to benefit and enhance the utility and value of their lands.
From the information furnished by the Township Supervisors it was found that each parcel of land in Menominee County could be assigned to some one of the following “intent in ownership classes”:
Residence. Land owned principally because of its value as a building site, land used for industrial, mercantile and residential purposes. This class also includes lumber yards and mili sites, bay shore land owned for commercial fishing purposes, land used as a site for a saloon, filling station or store, and all land which provides a home for people whose principal income is not derived from the land.
Farming. Land owned principally for farming purposes. Farms occupied by a tenant, farms known to be vacated only temporarily, and land bought for farming purposes but not yet occupied by the owner as a farm are included in this class.
Farm Abandonment. This class includes all lands that are recognized locally as abandoned farms. Land in this ciass has been vacated by the owner and will in all probability not again be occupied as a farm under the present ownership. There is but little abandoned farmland in this county that is non-productive or idle in the strictest sense. Neighboring farmers often crop part or all of the best fields and, as a rule, the hay land is mowed or grazed.
Speculation and Sale. Lands on the market if and when a buyer can be found.
Lands owned by land speculators, banks and mortgagees, and the cut-over holdings of lumber companies. These owners are giving no evidence that they themselves intend to develop or use the lands in this class.
Holding or Cutting Timber. Lands owned principally because of the timber growth, and consisting mainly of large tracts owned by companies and corporations as a timber reserve, but includes also scattered small tracts owned to provide winter work in the woods for the owner.
Mining. Land owned because of the gravel, clay or muck deposits found on it.
(It could not be definitely established that any lands in Menominee County are owned because of gas, oil, iron or other ore deposits.)
Water Poiver. Lands owned for water power development purposes.
^ •
Recreation. Land owned for recreational purposes, including waterfront resort property, and land owned for hunting or fishing camp sites.
Intent Unknown. Land held by owners whose intent in ownership is entirely unknown to the Township Supervisor. Includes a few farms abandoned long ago and since left idle and unused.
Public Lands. Lands owned by the County, State and U. S. Government.

Trucks and automobiles are replacing the horse for farm business travel and the marketing of farm produce in Menominee County. This shift toward economy of time in transportation is encouraged by the excellent rural road system that puts over half of the county’s farms on improved roads. Tractors, however, have not replaced horses to an equal extent for farm work. The U. S. Census reports 154 tractors on farms in 1924. It seems unlikely that motor power will very 1 completely replace the horse for farm work in Menominee County because the peculiar drumlin topography and strip swamp character of the main farm-belt region has imposed a farm lay-out of small and irregular shaped fields to fit the natural features.

In 1871 the Chicago and Northwestern Railroad was completed from Green { Bay, Wisconsin, to Menominee. During the following year this line was extended to . Powers and eastward to Escanaba. Its completion was an important event in the development of the county, for with this new transportation facility, the lumber industry was no longer restricted to river and lake transportation. Sawmills were soon located at many interior points, along the new railroad, and a large area of fertile land was made accessible for farm development. By 1880 over 5,000 acres of I	improved farmland had been occupied by agricultural development, which thereaf-
1	ter increased in area by about 20,000 acres during each ten-year period up to 1920.

According to the U. S. Census, Menominee County produced 5,868,845 gallons of milk in 1924 and sold dairy products valued at $732,326. It is interesting to note that the number of cows milked in 1924 was about 72 % of the total number of cattle i in the county. This is 13.5% higher thau the average for the state and in agreement with Menominee County’s prominence as a dairy county. Records compiled * by the county Agricultural Agent show that two creameries, sixteen cheese factories, fourteen cream stations and one milk depot were receiving milk and cream during 192S. Information on the amount of milk and cream handled was not available, but 438,384 pounds of butter and 3,190,464 pounds of American cheese are reported to have been manufactured during the same yea American cheese manufactured in Michigan in 1928.
- The 1,449 sheep reported by the 1925 Census are partly in, the small farm flocks that are scattered through the central farming belt and partly in the larger flocks that are maintained on a few less highly improved farms located on its western and northern margin.
Hog raising is not as importantly associated with the dairy farming here as in the southern part of the Lake States dairy region, where corn is a major feed crop. The average of about two swine per farm is made up largely by the hogs raised for home meat supply, and leaves an important market surplus on only a few farms.

Location of the areas of residence property can be inferred from Fig. 3 which shows the principal concentration of habitations. The acreage of farm abandonment was higher in the townships that possessed the most farm land but the percent of farmland abandoned was higher in the townships that had the least farmland. Recreation was most important along the Bay Shore and in Lake Township in the vicinity of the Shaky Lakes. The intent unknown lands are mainly in holdings distributed through the general area of “Forest Land on the market.” The public land occurs chiefly as scattered parcels throughout the area of “Forest Land on the market” and consists mainly of parcels that have reverted to State ownership through continued tax delinquency. Cedarville Township has the largest and most compact acreage of such land. The several County and State Parks occupy a portion of the public land.

The greatest increase in population came to Menominee County during the period from 1880 to 1890, when the population grew from 6,882 inhabitants to 20,570. This growth in population corresponds to the greatest expansion in the lumbering industry. During the next ten years the population continued to increase to a high total of 27,046 in 1900. At that time the city of Menominee was reported to have a population of 12,818. According to the U. S. Census, the total population of the county decreased to 23,778 inhabitants during the next 25 years a net loss of 3,268 inhabitants. This loss, however, was not evenly distributed \ throughout the county. It apparently consisted chiefly of laborers who departed as \ the lumbering operations declined, for during this period the city of Menominee ! lost about 3,900 inhabitants, and a few of the townships show a sufficient decrease j in population to account for a total loss of over 5,000 inhabitants. In the face of j this decrease, several agricultural townships, notably Stephenson and Holmes, have ; increased in population sufficiently to make the net loss only 3,268. It is, of course, i quite probable that a portion of what appears to have been a loss in population to v Menominee city was really merely a removal by some inhabitants from the city to the farm and a change in occupation from mill work to farming. (See Fig. 3 for present distribution of habitations.)

Menominee, the county seat, has over one-third of the county’s population. The facilities that this city enjoys for rail and lake shipping have maintained it as a manufacturing center and a distribution point for wholesale merchandise since the decline of the lumber industry. It is the gateway by which a great deal of the business and tourist travel from Wisconsin, Illinois and southward flows to the mining districts and the points of scenic and recreational attraction in the central portion of the Upper Peninsula. Being one of the principal northern cities on the popular round the lake” tourist tour brings Menominee additional transient trade. It is also the meeting and converging point for a considerable volume of freight shipments that are distributed from the Lower Peninsula and more eastern manufacturing centers into the territory to the north and west of Menominee.
It has a local trade area that dominates the southern part of the county, is strong as far north as Powers, and active over even a broader area in both Michigan and Wisconsin.
Stephenson, the next largest town, is located near the center of the county’s farm development. It serves a local trade area that extends across the county from the Green Bay shore to the Menominee River. This village is growing in population and importance in the affairs of the county.
The villages of Powers and Spalding are such close neighbors that the influence and interests of both are scarcely separable. They serve a relatively small farming area in the southern part of their combined local trade area, but both do a considerable business with transient trade. Powers is the junction point for the Green Bay-Escanaba-Iron Mountain branches of the Chicago and Northwestern Railway, and Spalding is located at the junction of the trunk line highways US-41 and US-2. The Delta-Menominee Tuberculosis Sanitarium is located about midway between these two villages.
Hermansville is the largest town in the northern part of the county. It is located at the junction of the Chicago-Northwestern Railway with the Soo Line, and has the home offices and mills of the IXL Lumber Company. The magnitude of this Company’s lumber productions draws a large amount of logs from beyond the limits of Menominee County to its Hermansville plant, where, among the usual lumber products, the manufacture of hard maple flooring is specialized. Hermansville is known as a village of model civic organization and attractiveness. It serves a prosperous and developing area of farm settlement.
Whitney, in the northeastern part of the county on the Metropolitan branch of the Chicago-Northwestern Railway, is the headquarters of the Whitney Farms enterprise. It is the shipping point for a small but developing farming community which the “company” store serves as a trading center.
The residents of three small areas on the Delta-Menominee County line find it more convenient to trade at Cornell, Bark River and Escanaba in Delta County, while a few farmers in the “Big Bend” of the Menominee River on the west side of the county trade mostly at Wausaukee, Wisconsin.
The general metropolitan business of the county is divided between the three cities, Menominee, Escanaba and Iron Mountain. Iron Mountain draws from the Faithom and Hermansville areas. Escanaba’s influence prevails in the Spalding-Powers, Wilson, Harris and other northeastern areas, while Menominee takes the general trade from the Nadeau trade area southward.
The nature and quantity of the county’s business and production is indicated by the carload exports of freight.

Menominee County has more land in farms and more farms than any other county in the Upper Peninsula, according to the U. S. Census of 1925. This agricultural leadership is maintained with only one-third of its area in farms and less than one-fifth of its area actually devoted to agricultural production. What are the other two-thirds contributing to the commercial and economic betterment of the county ? About one-eighth of the county’s area is held by lumber companies for the timber which it will yield or is now yielding. Land held for water power, mining, recreation, residence, accounts for an even smaller fraction of the county’s area.
The lands that are owned for the above purposes constitute the “Used Lands, which occupy 49.5% of the area of the county and account for 64.9% of its taxable wealth. The lands in these forms of ownership are the live and active assets •which, together with industry, are upholding the commercial and economic structure of the county. Improving their production and increasing their utility will continue to be an important and justifiable part of this county’s future development program.
The remaining 50.5% of the county is the so-called “Idle Land” area. Except for that portion of the public land that is now in County and State Parks, the idle land consists of unimproved cut-over lands and abandoned farmlands. This area is idle in the sense that it is not used for or definitely dedicated to any productive purpose, and its owners apparently have no intention of putting their holdings into productive use themselves. These lands are simply held for speculation or for sale when a buyer can be found. It, therefore, seems unlikely that any important development will be undertaken on the Idle Lands until the present owners either change their intent in ownership or the land is acquired by other owners—either private or public—who can find a productive use for it.	•
While these idle lands represent about half the area of the county, they account for only 11.7% of the total taxable wealth. In their present condition of use, or rather lack of use, they are. contributing but little ,_to the economic support of the county. By their low valuation and the fact that they harbor the most extensive and persistent tax delinquency, they are acting as a drag on the used and productive land so that the early development and use of the “Idle Land” is probably the county’s foremost development problem and one that should merit the urgent concern of the property owners, business men and County and State officials who wish to see Menominee County realize the fullest use of her land resources.

Poultry raising furnishes quite an important source of income to most of the farms through the eggs produced and birds marketed. The U. S. Census reports the value of chickens raised and eggs produced in 1924 at $223,589. This is about 30 % of the value of dairy products for the same year. This report does not include the income from the geese, ducks and turkeys raised for market.

The prevailing type of farming centers around dairying, with potatoes as the most common cash crop. Of course, some variation from this standard type of farm-1 ing is evident in certain communities and on individual farms. For instance, sugar beets were a fairly common market crop in 1925 in the vicinity of Stephenson, Carney, Wilson, Banat and Whitney. Southeast of Wiison several farmers were grow- i; ing peas, to be marketed as dry peas. Some of the Carpenter-Cook farms, near Menominee, were growing such muckland truck crops as cabbage, cauliflower, onions etc. On the sandy soils of the Menominee River Plains rye, buckwheat and potatoes were the main field crops.

The Chicago-Northwestern Railway is the principal carrier of the county’s freight and produce. Its main line from Chicago, Milwaukee and Green Bay extends northward through, the central part of the county to Powers, and then eastward to Escanaba. From Powers an important branch of this railroad extends northwestward through Hermansville to the Michigan iron mining district and beyond. The Metropolitan branch of the same railroad crosses the northern part of |	the county in a southeasterly direction to join the main line at Narenta, a few miles
i	east of the Menominee-Delta county line. The so-called “New Line” of the Chicago-
Northwestern crosses the county from east to west between the Iron Mountain-Powers-Escanaba line and the Metropolitan branch. The principal business of the New Line is hauling iron ore from the mines in the Iron Mountain district to the ore docks at Escanaba. It also provides an outlet for the forest products from the territory that it serves.
The main line of the Minneapolis, St. Paul and Sault Ste. Marie Railway (Soo Line) runs through the north central part of the county in a northeasterly direction, crossing the Wisconsin and Michigan R. R. at Faithorn and the Soo Line at Hermansville.

Onaway Loam (01). Thef Onaway Loam is the dominant soil in the drumlin region of the Gently Rolling Uplands and the most extensive upland soil in the county. It is a gently rolling ito rolling hardwood loam soil.
The Rodman Cobbly Loam is a well drained soil that was completely occupied by a forest of pine and hardwoods. Most of the ridge-like areas are too steep for plowland and are used mainly for pasture where cleared of forest growth. In the knobby hill areas some of the smoother portions have been cleared for cropland. It is a high lime soil that should be well suited to alfalfa and orcharding, but apt to
r
prove somewhat droughty for pasture land and general farm crops. It is an important source of gravel for building and highway purposes.
Rodman GraveUy Loam (ROl). The Rodman Gravelly Loam is a very common soil through the central part of the county. The areas that are shown on the soil map in the vicinity of Talbot and Daggett are good examples of this type which cannot be easily or accurately described because of the confusing manner with which the soil varies in character every few rods. It is chiefly a brown gravelly sandy loam, or loam with a more sandy and gravelly subsoil but spots of gravelly clay loam and also very sandy soil, either with or without gravel or stone, are so common that they appear in nearly every field. The surface features are equally variable, an intricate mess of low knolls, faint ridges and shallow depressions separated here by narrow strips and thereby broader stretches of smooth to flat land.
The natural drainage is good with a tendency to be too free and rapid on the gravelly knolls and sandy spots. This is a moderately productive soil that grew a variable mixture of pine and hardwoods. The original forest has nearly all been cut. The second growth stands usually contain considerable aspen and generally some young pine mixed with the common hardwood species. Approximately one-third of this soil has been cleared for pasture and cropland.
Mancelona Sandy Loam (Msl). This sandy loam is a common soil on the nearly level areas between the drumlins throughout the central part of the county. It is a well drained light brown sandy loam soil that is underlain at about 1% to 2 feet by a gravelly sandy subsoil. Ordinarily the surface soil is also slightly gravelly, but some areas show no gravel in the plow soil.
The Mancelona Sandy Loam resembles the Mancelona Loam rather closely except that it has a more sandy surface soil and a less gravelly subsoil. It is readily distinguished from the Rodman Gravelly Loam by its smoother surface features and more uniform soil.
The Mancelona Sandy Loam is a moderately productive soil that was occupied by a forest of mixed hardwood, hemlock and pine. About half of this soil has been cleared for farmland. Oats, rye, corn, potatoes, clover and timothy are the principal crops. Alfalfa is grown to some extent. The yields of most field crops average somewhat lower and pastures usually show the effect of dry weather sooner on this soil than on the heavier loam soils.
Longrie Fine Sandy Loam (Lfsl). This is a smooth to nearly level fine sandy loam soil that is underlain at shallow depths by limestone bed rock. Shelving out crops of the bedrock, slabs of limestone and scattered boulders cause this soil to be moderately stony to stony in character. It is a common but not extensive type in the northern part of the county in the vicinity of Faunus and northward. Only a few small areas have been cleared for farmland and these are used mainly for pasture. The original forest growth wras a mixture of hardwoods, hemlock and white pine. The virgin stands have been cut and the young second growth contains considerable poplar and white birch with maple and a variable amount of white pine, balsam and spruce.

On the Soil Map, all of the soils which belong to a single group 'have been given the same color, but a different color has been used for each group. For example, the six Light Sandy Soils all have the same yellow color, while the four Swamp and Marsh Soils all have the same green color. Each different soil is marked by its own letter symbol and limited by a soil boundary. Therefore, in using the soil map, the color indicates at a glance whether the soil is sandy or loamy or swampy; the letter symbol designates the particular kind of sandy or loamy or swampy soil; and the location of the soil boundary marks the limit of that particular soil and shows where it borders on some other soil of a different character, The name for any soil and the description of its character are found by locating the corresponding color block and letter symbol in the Key to Soils.

Wallace Fine Sand (WEfs). The Wallace Fine Sand occupies the dry sandy knolls and narrow winding ridges of the Lake Plain and the south central part of the county. This sandy soil is easily distinguished by its knolly or ridgey surface features and the fact that it is free from gravel or stone. It has a pale gray fine sandy surface soil on a. deep sandy subsoil that is dark rusty or coffee brown colored in the upper part and yellow below a depth of two or three feet. The dark brown layer and the upper part of the underlying yellow layer are usually cemented into a brittle sandy hardpan. This soil is dry, droughty and very acid. Its natural forest growth was mainly Norway and white pine, which accounts for its being referred to as “Norway Ridges.” This soil is not used to any important extent for farmland. A few farmsteads and gardens have been located on it because of its very good drainage, but the bulk of the cleared area is used for pasture rather than cropland.

Menominee County has an area of 667,450 acres or about 1,043 square miles. Only 2,376 acres of this area consists of water surface in inland lakes and ponds.
WATER RESOURCES
Hayward Lake and North LaJjo, Menominee County’s two largest inland lakes, are both shallow, muck bottom lakes with swampy shores that offer but little attraction for intensive resort (cottage and summer hotel) development. They a„r&, however, visited to a considerable extent by duck hunters for the fall shooting. The chain of Shaky Lakes in the west central part of Lake Township is more popular with the summer season vacationists. The Green Bay shore and the Menominee River have attracted the bulk of the Cottage type of recreational development.
The improvement of the bay shore road, M-35, froni Menominee to Escanaba has made practically the entire stretch of this interesting and inviting shore easily accessible for i-esortj development. As a result, the earlier cottage colonies north of Henes Park at Long Beach and Utopia Beach have grown rapidly, and more recently new groups of cottages have been added at many of the most accessible and attractive locations between Menominee and Cedar River village or beyond. While private development is acquiring the ba^
cess to its enjoyment by the John W. Wells State Park at Cedar River and the three County Parks that reserve attractive areas of the shore and adjacent woodland.
The Menominee River recreation development is more in the nature of individual cottages or hunting camps that are less closely grouped than on the bay shore. Wallace Resort and Borost Resort are the only resort subdivisions to date. The power dams that aye being planned for the White Rapids and Chalk Hill sites will create flowage areas that will be virtually lakes.

The Menominee River drains an area of about 4,100 square miles in Wisconsin and Michigan. The three installed power developments, two in the city of Menominee and one west of Ingalls, do not utilize the full power possibilities of this stream in Menominee County. According to this survey’s water power inventory, six additional power sites are available for development between the upper dam in the city of Menominee and the point where the river enters the county. These six sites are estimated to be capable of developing 22,500 K. W. at 70% efficiency. (See report on the Water Resources of the Menominee River in Menominee County, 1926, by C. O. Wisler.) Preliminary work is now under way for the development of the Chalk Hill and While Rapids sites.
The power inventory of the Big Cedar River shows that there is no site on this stream capable of furnishing sufficient power for a commercial project, but a number of sites are capable of furnishing power for small industries or farm use.

The Lake Plain is a comparatively low, level area bordering Green Bay and extending inland for a distance of 3 to 6 miles. This plain has a general elevation of less than 100 feet above the present level of Lake Michigan. It owes its flatness to the fact that it was at one time covered by a higher stage of the Great Lakes. During that time the Lake Plain received, first, clayey, and later, sandy deposits v of lake sediment. The present mineral soils have been formed from these lake-laid sediments. Because of its general flatness, low elevation and the underlying clay, the natural drainage is slow and sluggish and a large amount of wet, poorly drained, swamp and swamp border soil has developed. These wet lands are broken by patches and strips of nearly level sandy soil, low narrow ridges of gravelly soil, island-like areas of loam soil and low knolls of wind drifted sand, all of which help to confuse and retard the free runoff of surface drainage.
The . original forest growth has practically all been cut from the Lake Plain division. On the dry sandy soils Norway pine and white pine were the dominant forest growth, 'while the more moist sandy soils were occupied by purer stands of white pine. The hardwood forest was confined to the few island-like areas of stony loam soil and the low strip-like ridges of gravelly soil. The shallow swamp soils had a mixed stand of swamp hardwoods and swamp conifers which gave way to almost pure stands of swamp conifers (cedar, tamarack, spruce) on the deep swamps.



Roselawn Loamy Sand (Rls). The Roselawn Loamy Sand is an extensive soil on the rolling to hilly uplands (moraines) east of the Menominee River. It differs from the other Light Sandy Soils by being somewhat gravelly and stony and in having streaks and pockets of gritty gravelly sandy clay hidden in the deep sandy subsoil in a hit and miss sort of fashion. Where these sandy clay layers are close to the surface, the surface soil is usually also quite loamy. The fact that this is a rolling to hilly sandy soil that is not free from gravel or stone serves to distinguish it most readily and definitely from the other Light Sandy Soils which are either decidedly more level or else entirely free from gravel or stone.
The open porous nature of the sandy surface soil and subsoil causes the Roselawn Loamy Sand to drain rapidly and freely. The rainfall is so rapidly absorbed that but little surface runoff occurs, and both moisture and fertility are easily lost into the underdrainage as a consequence. Normal yields of the common farm crops average moderate to low on this soil even in favorable seasons, while in dry seasons the scanty native pasturage becomes very short in mid-season and “near crop failures” have been experienced.
The virgin forest growth on the Roselawn Loamy Sand was dominantly Norway and white pine. The original stand probably included a variable amount of oaks (red, scarlet and white) and jack pine on the more sandy portions, and likely also some maple, beech and hemlock on the more loamy patches. The merchantable stands of the virgin pine have all been logged off and most of the cutover land has been burned over once or oftener by forest fires. Those less severely burned portions which have escaped reburning in recent years are now mainly covered by a second growth stand of poplar and white birch, oak or jack pine, but the areas which have been severely and frequently reburned are now occupied only by a few scattered
N
oaks and an open clumpy growth of upland willow and red maple brush with sweet fern, patchy moss carpets, and a sparse growth of native upland grasses between the charred and blackened stumps. The Roselawn Loamy Sand has not been cleared to any important extent for farmland.
Grayling Sand (GGs). The Grayling Sand is a dry sandy soil that occurs on the level plains that border the Menominee River. To a casual observation, this soil might seem to differ but little from the other level Light Sandy Soils;—the Rubicon, Saugatuck and Eastport Sand—but careful inspection will reveal the differences that are shown in the Soil Profile Diagrams of these sandy soils and which emphasize the fact that the undisturbed Grayling Sand has (1) only a very thin layer of dull gray sand under the scanty surface cover of plant litter and mold; (2) that the sandy subsurface layer has a uniform light brow;n color and shows no tendency to cement into a “sandy hardpan”; and (3) that the subsoil is a plain yellowish colored loose open sand. These characteristics of the soil itself are as constant as its uniformly sandy character, its very free and rapid natural underdrainage and its dry, droughty nature which is made so strikingly apparent by the appearance of the natural vegetation.	...
The virgin forest growth on the Grayling Sand was made up mainly of a rather open stand of slow growing Norway pine and dense but patchy and ragged clumps of jack pine with sweetfern, moss carpets and native grass on the open fire cleared areas. White pine and oaks were also present but very much in the minority. The logging of the virgin pine left only a few scattered cull trees and patches of undersized growth. In competition with fires and jack pine these have been unable to reseed the cutover lands so that the present forest growth is mainly jack pine with stunted oak and poplar.
Even though the Grayling Sand is invitingly level and comparatively easy to clear, its droughtiness and low natural fertility make it an uninviting prospect for agricultural'use. There is scarcely any farm development on this soil.
Rubicon Sand (RNs). The Rubicon Sand occurs on the moderately moist sandy plains. In soil character, in topographic position, in degree of drainage, in productivity, in the variety and thriftiness of its natural vegetation, in fact, in practically every respect, this soil is intermediate in character between the dry Grayling Sand and the more moist Saugatuck Sand. This intermediate character is its outstanding mark of distinction.
Saugatuck Sand (Ss). The Saugatuck Sand is the most extensive sandy soil on the Lake Plain. It occupies positions but slightly higher than the wet lands or swamps which it commonly borders. The surface featui-es, while flat in a broad way, are faintly moundy and ridgey. The underdrainage is slow due either to a naturally shallow ground water level or to underlying layers of tight heavy clay at or below five feet in depth which prevent free subsoil drainage. These conditions cause every slight sag and swale to be wet and poorly drained, while the faint mounds and low swell-like ridges are dry on the surface but moist in the deep subsoil. As a result, the areas of Saugatuck Sand are patchy in soil character. The low mounds and ridges have a soil character like that shown in the Profile Diagram; i. e., a foot or so of leached appearing pale gray sand, underlain by a dark coffee brown sandy “hardpan” of variable depth which grades downward into a yellowish or spotted, moist to wret, sandy subsoil. The intervening wet sags and swales are occupied by Granby Sand or shallow deposits of Swamp and Marsh Soils.




The highly developed farming communities from Menominee northward pasil Stephenson to beyc nd Hermantyille, Powers and Wilson are located principally onk this soil. Clover, timothy, oaits, barley, potatoes and corn are the common farm® crops. Wheat, sw< et clover, ajfalfa, peas and sugar beets are grown in small fields^™1 on some of the far. is.
