Menominee Fine Sandy Loam (MEfsl). This is the~ prevailing upland fine sandy loam soil in the southern part of the county near the junction of the Little River and the Menominee River. It is a smooth rolling brown fine sandy loam or loamy fine sand that is quite free from gravel or stone in the surface layers. This soil is underlain by the same reddish limey gravelly sandy clay that underlies the Onaway Fine Sandy Loam but at greater depth (see Soil Profile Diagrams). It is better drained than the lower-lying Ogemaw Fine Sandy and smoother and less stony or gravelly than the Emmet Fine Sandy Loam.
The virgin forest growth on the Menominee Fine Sandy Loam varied from nearly clear stands of pine to mixed pine, hemlock and hardwoods. It is a fairly productive soil when carefully farmed. To the northwest of Menominee, this soil has been quite completely cleared for farmland and is used chiefly for the regular farm crops of timothy and clover hay, oats, potatoes, and smaller fields of corn, beans and alfalfa.
Emmet Fine Sandy Loam (Efsl). This soil is intermediate in character and productiveness between the Roselawn Loamy Sand and the Onaway Fine Sandy Loam. It is the common light sandy loam soil of the hilly belt that lies between the gently rolling uplands of the central part of the county and the Menominee River. It also occurs in scattered areas through the north central part of the county from Hermansville northward.
This soil is ordinarily rather stony and gravelty though it varies in this respect even within a single forty-acre tract. The normally rolling to somewhat hilly surface features insure good to rather free natural drainage.
The virgin forest growth was mainly white and Norway pine with a variable amount of hemlock, maple, beech and elm.. This forest growth has been logged off on all but parts of the areas in the north central part of the county. The second growth stands contain a considerable amount of poplar and white birch, as a rule, and far less pine than the original growth. The cut over areas that have been severely burned in the past are occupied by sweetfern and bracken with an open brushy growth of maple, elm and poplar and some few cull pine that were left by the loggers.
This soil has been more generally cleared for farmland along the main road from Swanson to Longrie and in the region between Kelly Creek and the Menominee River than elsewhere in the county. Timothy and clover for hay, oats, rye and potatoes are the principal crops, with a small acreage of corn, beans, buckwheat and an occasional small field of alfalfa.
. Ingalls Fine Sandy Loam (Ifsi). This soil occurs on the level benches that border the present bottomlands of the Menominee River and its main tributaries. The surface soil is prevailingly a brown mellow fine sandy loam except in a few areas that are somewhat more sandy than the average. The subsoil consists of alternating thin layers of fine sand, fine sandy loam, silt and clay. This soil is free from stone. The benches that it occupies are, as a rule, about 10 to 25 feet higher than the present bottomlands, so that the natural drainage is at least fairly good. There are only about 1,500 acres of this soil in the county, but nearly half of this has been cleared for cropland and pasture. Timothy, clover, oats, corn and some potatoes and buckwheat on the drier portions are the crops that were being most commonly grown on this soil.
Ogemavj Fine Sandy Loam (OWfsl). This soil occurs only in rather small scattered and patchy areas. It is a comparatively low lying soil and occurs on moist footslopes or flat to smooth areas. It resembles the Saugatuck Sand in the appearance of its surface soil and in its generally flat but low moundy surface features which retard free surface drainage. On the other hand, this soil differs from the Saugatuck Sand in having a more loamy surface soil and by being underlain with clay at a much shallower depth. This clayey subsoil prevents free underdrainage and keeps the soil just above the clay either moist or saturated most of the time. As a result of the retarded drainage, every shallow sag or swale is occupied by a spot or narrow strip of Bergland Loam, and the broader, deeper depressions are likely to be even more swampy and wet.
In the northern part of the county a deep phase of this soil was found. These areas are not separately shown on the soil map. They differ from the regular soil mainly in that the clayey subsoil may be as much as 3 or 5 feet below the surface.
The virgin forest growth on the Ogemaw Fine Sandy Loain consisted chiefly of large fast growing white pine. In some places this pine grew in practically clear stands, but quite as often where variations in the natural drainage favored them, any or all of the following species, hemlock, maple, ash, elm, basswood, and balsam, cedar, tamarack and spruce entered into the stand. The present second growth forest cover shows an equally variable mixture, but in which poplar, alder and willow are often very prominent, while the hemlock and pine are quite apt to be entirely absent.
The principal areas of this soil are still uncleared. Those that have been fitted for farmland are'used mostly for pasture and hay. Timothy and alsike make fair to moderate yields, and the improved pasture land carries well through the season. The wetter parts, at least, are inclined to be too cold and late for the common and cultivated crops unless some drainage improvement is provided.

Granby Sand (Gs). The Granby Sand occurs chiefly where the better drainecl Light Sandy So ls occupy the adjoining higher ground. This sandi subsoil distinguishes it from the Bergland soils, which are underlain by heavy claj at comparatively shallow depths. CLIMATE
Menominee County is a lake border county that rises about 500 feet above the lake as it extends inland and northward to a distance of about 40 miles. In consequence, the northwestern portion of the county experiences a shorter growing season, greater extremes of temperature in both summer and winter, and a heavier snow fall than the southeastern portion adjacent to the lake shore. These differences between the interior and lake shore weather are evidenced by the U. S. Weather Bureau observations at Powers, which may be taken as representative of the north central part of the county, and the similar records for Menominee that represent the southern and lake shore region.

The natural vegetation was, of course, just as variable as the soil, and the virgin conditions have been still further complicated by cutting and subsequent fires. In general, the sandy mounds and swells were covered by a stand of large, fast growing white pine with here and there some Norway pine. The wet sags and swales were occupied by the common swamp forests or patches of marsh and bog vegetation. On the cutover lands that have not been too recently burned, the sandy mounds -sure now usually covered with a dense stand of straight fast growing poplar mixed with a variable amount of white birch, sand cherry, red maple, elm, etc., and occasionally also some balsam fir and white pine reproduction. Bracken, blueberry and wintergreen are common in the ground cover and make an unusually thrifty growth. Except where the original marsh or bog vegetation has persisted,, the sags and swales are now occupied either by a dense thicket growth of poplar, willow and alder or a second growth of the original swamp forest.

This group includes the dej*p muck and peat soils; i. e., those swamp, marsh ai I bog soils which are at least so deep that their natural vegetation roots and feeds i the muck or peat or that when jfarmed their cropped land has a muck or peat so which exceeds the normal deptf. of plowing and cultivation.
•4*
These muck and peat soiy have been formed by the broken up and partly d»l cayed remains from the countless generations of natural vegetation that have grow in and on the wet, poorly drained situations which these soils now occupy. The differ according to the nature of the vegetation from which they were derived ar^| the degree of drainage under \j/hich they have accumulated. Those which have aJ cumulated under very poor drainage are least decayed, while those which wei formed under somewhat betteri drainage are more completely decayed.
Greenwood Peat (G). The Greenwood Peat occurs in the open treeless bogs an wet marshes. This is a yellowish brown, raw, coarse, fibrous peat which has decaye but slightly and is very strongly acid as a rule. The height of the natural watei table varies from at or near the surface to as much as five or six feet below the su^l face, according to the season and the rainfall. During the spring or in very wet se, sons these bogs and marshes are very wet, but during the late summer and ear fall they often become very dry. This peat is not used for either crops or pastur Its only present value is for the wild blueberries and cranberries and the Sphaj num moss that may be gathered on the bogs and the coarse “marsh grass” that : occasionally cut on the marshes for topping haystacks and sheds.	I
Spalding Peat (G). The Spalding Peat occurs in the spruce-tamarack swam pi It is a brown, slightly to moderately decayed, mixed fibrous and woody peat that underlain at one to two feet by a more yellowish, raw, coarse fibrous peat. This a strongly acid, moderately wet swamp soil in which the normal watertable seldoj falls to more than a foot beneath the surface.
The Spalding Peat is scarcely ever used for either crops or pasture. It is occj pied by a rather slow growing stand of spruce and tamarack that may or may nj include a few cedar.
Houghton Muck (H). The Houghton Muck is the common marshland soil. I consists of a dark brown to nearly black, rather well decayed, finely fibrous peat <1 muck in the surface three feet. The more recently accumulated surface layer is s« dom so well decayed as the material just below. The Houghton Muck is seldom mol than mildly acid. The natural watertable normally stands between one and tvl feet below the surface for most of the summer. This muck soil is not being cultl vated to any important extent. It is pastured some and the natural growth of blul joint and sedges is rather regularly harvested in some localities for “marsh hayl
Rifle Peat (R). The Rifle Peat occurs in those swamps that are or were col ered by a dense thrifty forest of tamarack, cedar and spruce with a variable mil ture of elm, ash, soft maple and scattered white pine. This swamp soil is a dal brown or nearly black, moderately decayed woody peat to a depth of 2 feet, whefc

MEDIUM LOAM SOILS
The five soils in this group are all well drained, productive, upland hardwood soils. Aside from this similarity they are plainly different.
Mancelona Loam (Ml). This soil occurs in only a few places in the central part of the county. It occupies smooth to nearly level area of glacial outwash between the drumlins. The Mancelona Loam has a somewhat gravelly and cobbly brown loam surface soil and a more gravelly (high lime) subsoil, miles west of Daggett is a good example of this soil, from the Longrie Loam and the Posen Stony Loam, because these two nearly level loam soils are more stony in the surface soil and underlain at rather shallow depths by limestone bedrock instead of gravel.
The Mancelona Loam is a well-drained, productive soil that had a virgin forest cover of maple, basswood and elm in which there was a variable amount of cedar, balsam, tamarack and white pine. This soil has been quite completely cleared for farmland. Timothy and clover, oats, wheat, corn for silage, and potatoes are the principal farm crops. This soil is well suited to alfalfa, and this crop is being grown by quite a few of the farmers on the Mancelona Loam.
Longrie Loam (LI). The Longrie Loam is a common soil from Longrie northward past Powers and Hermansville to the north central part of the county. It occupies those smooth to nearly level uplands between the drumlins that are underlain at shallow depth by limestone bedrock. The soil above the bedrock varies from a few inches to several feet in depth. Shelving outcrops of the limestone come to the surface here and there, but ordinarily only in small patches. Where the soil is less than 2 feet deep it consists of a brown mellow stony loam, and where it exceeds that depth the brown loam surface soil is ordinarily underlain by rather reddish sandy clay subsoil above the bedrock.
The natural drainage is good except on the occasional seepy spots where the bedrock brings the underdrainage to the surface. The original forest growth on this soil consisted of a few large white pine among a stand of maple, elm, ash, hemlock, balsam and cedar. The second growth stands are a variable mixture of these species and poplar.
This soil has been less generally cleared for farmland than the deeper and more rolling Onaway Loam. Where both these soils occur on the same farm, the more stony Longrie Loam is used more for pasture and the cropland is placed as
much as possible on the Onaway Loam. They are both productive soils, however, and are used for the same crops when fitted for plowland.
Posen Stony Loam (PNsl). This is a common but not extensive soil from Menominee northeastward to the Delta County Line. Like the Longrie Loam, it is underlain at shallow depths by limestone bedrock, but differs from that soil mainly in having a more clayey subsoil above the bedrock and in being somewhat less perfectly drained. The Posen Stony Loam is smoother, more stony, less perfectly drained and underlain at shallower depths by limestone bedrock than the Onaway Loam, but this difference is hard to establish since no very distinct change could be found between these two soils where Posen Stony Loam graded off into those areas on the Onaway Loam that are rather smooth and somewhat more stony than the average.

The southern pajrt of the county has an average growing season that exceeds 14.0 days. This is about'1 equal to the average growing season that prevails in the vicinity of St. Johns and Owosso in the central part of the Lower Peninsula of Michigan. The northwestern part of the county, however, has a growing season that is at least 30 days shorter and more like that which prevails in the vicinity of Grayling and Gaylord in the north central part of the Lower Peninsula.

The Saugatuck Sand has not been used much for farmland. It occupies rather low frosty situations and generally requires some artificial draining in addition to the usual clearing costs. The areas which have been improved are mainly located on farms where the bulk of the cropland consists of heavier, better drained and more durable soils so that the Saugatuck Sand can be used mostly for pasture and . hay crops.

The Gently Rolling Upland borders on the western margin of the Lake Plain in a wedge shaped area that extends the full length of the county to expand beyond the eastern and western limits of the county in its northward extension. This division covers the “till plain” region and includes some of the finest examples of drumlin topography” in the Lake States region. These drumlins—low, oblong, smooth, sloping hills, trending in a northeast-southwest direction—are an outstanding feature of the landscape. They vary in width from less than a quarter of a mile, for the smaller ones, up to a mile for some of the larger ones. Most of them are from one-half to one and a half miles in length. Only the larger ones exceed this length, though frequently several are so closely grouped that they make up a continuous area of gently rolling upland. Ordinarily, however, each drumlin is separated from its neighbors by a surrounding flat or narrow valley. These intervening flats or valleys are usually partly or entirely occupied by swamp and swamp border soils so that the Gently Rolling Upland division really includes a considerable total area of poorly drained land in the strip swamps that lie between the drumlins. The gently rolling uplands are, however, sufficiently sloping to have good and thorough natural drainage. In fact, parts of the side slopes of some of the high and narrow drumlins are so steep that they are easily damaged by erosion if cultivated.
In the southern part of the county this division has a general elevation of about 650 to 750 feet above sea level or about 75 to 150 feet above Lake Michigan. Through its northward extension the general elevation gradually rises until it reaches an altitude of 900 to 1,050 feet above sea level in the northwestern part of the county. Practically nowhere, however, do the local differences between the hill-crests and the neighboring lowlands exceed 150 feet.
The prevailing soil on these gently rolling uplands is a well drained brown loam or sandy loam on a more reddish and moderately clayey, high lime drift. _
The virgin forest growth on the well drained loam soils was chiefly hard maple, beech, yellow birch and hemlock with some ironwood, elm, white ash, basswood and an occasional white pine. The low-lying swamp soils and swamp forest growth, which consisted mainly of white cedar, tamarack and spruce. In the shallow swamps and on the swamp border soils the stand include a variable amount of soft maple, ash, elm and some white pine in association with the common swamp conifers. In the few pothole bogs the natural growth was and still is chiefly leather leaf, blueberry, cranberry and sphagnum moss. The wet lands were dominantly forest land, however, for the few strips of sedge and bluejoint meadow along some of the streams occupy only a small part of the swamp soils.
The Hilly Belt borders the western side of the Gently Rolling Uplands in a strip which has a width of from two to eight miles. This division covers the morainic section of the county and includes the rougher western margin of the till plain re-
averages moderately high at all seasons. Ordinarily about 150 days in efch year are cloudy, 100 days are clear and 115 days are re-ported as partly clokdy. The warm season, April to September, inclusive, usually
s
receives about two-thirds of the total average annual precipitation. The rainfall generally comes in gentle rains or showers. Cloudbursts, hailstorms and tornados are quite rare, though evidence of past wind and hailstorms is given by the old windfalls in the forest and the hail marks on the trunks of the few" remaining large Norway pines. The) Weather Bureau data indicates that the average number of days with hail during the frostless season is at least three times greater in the hail belt of the Plains States than in the vicinity of Menominee County.
The first snowfall in autumn usually comes during the latter part of October. Ordinarily, the ground is covered with snow for from 90 to 120 days each winter. Freezing and sub-zero weather is common from November to April, but there are many pleasant winter days when the temperature rises to above freezing. The winter breakup” commonly comes late in March and is soon followed by real spring weather. The summer season is pleasant with warm days, cool nights and an invigorating atmosphere that permits exertion in either labor or recreation without oppressive fatigue.
Grains, clover, alfalfa, timothy and other hardy field crops and vegetables are grown throughout tfje county. Corn is ordinarily grown to maturity in the southern portion and to tjie ensilage stage in the central section. Both corn and potatoes are sometimes damaged before maturity by untimely early frosts in the northern part of the county arid are not certain to escape some injury even in the central part. Pastures carry well throughout the season from late spring to late fall and very rarely “burn out” badly in midsummer. The peculiar drumlin topography seems to work out advantageously in this regard by giving practically every farm some low lying land suitable fir heavy midseason grazing.

Eastport Sand (Ets). The Eastport Sand is the level, moderately dry to dry sandy soil that borders the shore of Green Bay. It is a dull gray sandy soil with a yellowish sandy subsoil that is generally high in lime.
The natural forest growth on this soil was mainly hemlock and pine mixed with elm, birch and maple. The cutover portions are now occupied chiefly by a second growth of birch, beech and maple with a variable amount of poplar, white birch, cherry, cedar, balsam, tamarack and willow'.
From Ingallston to Arthur Bay the Eastport Sand has been cleared to some extent for farmland. Here it is used for pasture, hay, grain, potatoes and gardens.

LIGHT LOAM SOILS
The Light Loam Soils might be designated as “mixed pine and hardwood lands.” These soils, as the nature of their virgin forest would lead one to suspect, are intermediate in productiveness between the sandy pine lands and the heavier loam hardwood lands. Their distinguishing features are not easy to read, but are somewhat obscurely hidden in the nature of their surface soils and subsoils.
Alpena Cobbly Loam (AAl). This soil occurs only on the Lake Plain. It occupies the low swells and strip-like ridges that mark the position of the shore lines and shoals of the ancient glacial lakes. The brown gravelly and cobbly surface soil is underlain at less than two feet by loose open beds of cobble, gravel and sand. This soil is well drained and high in lime. It was occupied by a virgin forest in which maple, beech, hemlock, balsam and cedar were .common. This is the only soil in the Light Loam Group on which pine was not common in the forest growth. It is a productive soil but difficult t<£ cultivate. Because of its limey character and good natural drainage, this soil should be well adapted to alfalfa, sweet clover and orchards.
Rodman Cobbly Loam (ROl). This soil is found only on the cobbly, knobby hills (kames) like those north of Koss and the narrow, winding, steep sided “hogs-back” ridges (eskers) like the one that crosses the highway about one-half mile south of Carbondale and extends southwesternly through the swamp for about 5 miles. This soil is readily distinguished from the smoother Rodman Gravelly Loam by these distinctive surface features and its decidedly cobbly character. It can hardly be confused with the Wallace Fine Sand, which has somewhat similar surface features, because that sandy soil is entirely free from gravel and stones.

AD ISON’S ZOO, with all of the great zoological families represented, excepting the giraffe, located at Henry Vilas Park, is worthy of a part of your time. The young folks will enjoy the animals and the birds.
H, for a horseback canter along the wooded paths and lakeshore drives! Horses, especially trained, with instructors, are available for you and your friends.

BOUT our city are four beautiful chain lakes, giving a water course of about thirty miles. Motor boats will spin you about between dips and help cultivate a healthy coat of tan and an excellent appetite.
UMEROUS are the camping and picnic spots in and around Madison, where you can enjoy the great outdoors. At Monona Park there has been a free camp site for tourists for a number of years. Ask caretaker.

ELLS of Wisconsin. This famous beaLity spot is a popular motor trip from Madison. You can motor there and back in a day. Local motor service available. Ask the Association of Commerce.
ILL you be interested in “casting” when you come to Madison? There’s a club waiting to take you in as a member. Members of the club will help you find the fishing grounds.

S THERE a more delightful shore than this on which to boat, swim, sail or canoe during your summer vacation days? Why not see Madison, “the city built upon an isthmus,” this summer?
NDULGING in aquatic sports is a part of the daily life of men, women and children, who have the good fortune to live or sojourn in Madison. Hundreds of canoes are “at sea” daily.
OME prefer golf. There are two excellent 18-hole courses, the Maple Bluff Golf Club and the Black Hawk Golf Club. Both clubs are on Lake Mendota. Bring your sticks with you.
INCL there are numerous cennis courts in the parks and on the University of Wisconsin Campus, arrangements can be made for the use of many of them by visitors to “the four lake city.”
Some Facts on Madison
POPULA I ION: City of Madison—45,000 (including 7,418 resident students at the University of Wisconsin; Retail Trade Area— 40 mile radius about city, 302,665; Wholesale Trade Area—855,078
AL I I TUDE: 84-5 feet above sea level.
AREA: 6.35 square miles.
LENGTH: 8 miles.
LAKES: Mendota, “Gathering of the Waters”—25 miles in cir-cumferencej Monona, "Spirit”—11 miles in circumference; Waubesa, "Swan”; Kegonsa, "Fish”; Wingra, "Dead." Public launch, sail boat and canoe service. Municipal boat and bath houses. Many public piers.
PARKS: 20, containing 280 acres. (University grounds—1,000 acres.) One of best zoological gardens in the Middle West. Eleven miles of lake shore in city and suburbs under control. 1 50 miles of streets 30 miles of pleasure drives. Over $450,000 spent on city parks and drives.
INDUSTRIES: 60 manufacturing concerns employ 4,500 people; annual value of products $15,000,000. Principal products: machine tools, dry batteries, including wireless batteries, chemicals, shoes, candy, farm machinery, drugs, ice cream and dairy products.
STATE CAPITOL: Wisconsin' s new state capitol located here the most striking piece of monumental architecture in America.
EDUCATIONAL CENTER: The University of Wisconsin, 2 high schools, 15 public schools, 5 parochial schools, "4 C” College of Commerce, 2 private schools, a vocational school, and 3 schools of music have 17,454 children and adults, or more than one-third of the population of the city, taking either full or part-time work. Invested in University—$10,000,000; in city schools—$2,000,000. Over 983,000 volumes in the libraries of the city.
TORES I PRODUC I S LABORATORY: Only institution of the kind in America.
TRANSPOR I A I ION: 3 railroads with 9 lines make city an excellent jobbing and wholesale centre.
PUBLIC UTILITIES: Modern street railway system. Up-to-date gas and electric plants. Electric power rates cheapest in Wisconsin. Water works plant with capacity of 7.500,000 gallons per day. Water taken from 10 artesian wells. City has 12,738 telephones, largest number per capita of any city in the world.
BUILDING PERMITS: Last year—$2,891,628.
ASSESSED VALUATION: Over $82,000,000.
BANKS: Resources—$21,810,470. Clearings—$93,814,934.
SUMMER TRAVEL: Madison is the greatest motor tourist gathering point east of the Rockies. Free Camp Sites. Fifty trains daily. Cottages available. For special information write to the
Madison Association of Commerce
